hkennar, Stirlingshire, Schotland"},"en":{"10 Jan 1540–1600":"10 January 1540–1600","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1550–1585":"1550–1585","1550–1604":"1550–1604","1555–1640":"1555–1640","1560–1587":"1560–1587","1560–1604":"1560–1604","1541–1600":"1541–1600","1570–1604":"1570–1604","1570–1616":"1570–1616","1520–1600":"1520–1600","1535–1640":"1535–1640","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","10 Jan 1540":"10 January 1540","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1541":"1541","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","1616":"1616","1604":"1604","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Bothkennar, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Bothkennar, Stirlingshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rankin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English: from Middle English <i>Ran(d)kin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Ran(d)</i>, a pet form of the personal name <i>Ran(d)ulf</i>. See   Rand  ,   Randolph  ,   Randall  . This name was brought to Northern Ireland (Derry) from Scotland in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Rankine","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Rankin  ."]},{"name":"Rand","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Rand</i>, a pet form of <i>Randolf</i>. Compare   Randolph  ,   Randall  ,   Randy  , and see also   Rance  .","English: habitational name from Rand (Lincolnshire), Rand Grange (North Yorkshire), or Raunds (Northamptonshire), all of which derive from Old English <i>rand</i> ‘edge, border, rim’.","German: from a short form of any of various ancient Germanic compound personal names formed with <i>rand</i> ‘rim (of a shield)’. Compare 1 above."]},{"name":"Rankins","meanings":["English (London): variant of   Rankin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Rank","meanings":["English: nickname for a powerfully built man or someone of violent emotions, from Middle English <i>rank</i> ‘proud, headstrong, stout-hearted’ (Old English <i>ranc</i> ‘proud, rebellious’).","English: from a Middle English personal name <i>Ranke</i>, a back-formation from the diminutive   Rankin  .","South German: variant of   Rang   2. This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When James Rankin was born on 10 January 1540, in Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland, his father, John James Rankin, was 20 and his mother, Mary Polly Lineberger, was 5. He married Jane Elizabeth Phelps. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1600, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 60."},"et":{"10 Jan 1540–1600":"10. jaanuar 1540–1600","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1550–1585":"1550–1585","1550–1604":"1550–1604","1555–1640":"1555–1640","1560–1587":"1560–1587","1560–1604":"1560–1604","1541–1600":"1541–1600","1570–1604":"1570–1604","1570–1616":"1570–1616","1520–1600":"1520–1600","1535–1640":"1535–1640","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","10 Jan 1540":"10. jaanuar 1540","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1541":"1541","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","1616":"1616","1604":"1604","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Bothkennar, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Bothkennar, Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"10 Jan 1540–1600":"10. tammikuuta 1540–1600","1540–1600":"1540–1600","1550–1585":"1550–1585","1550–1604":"1550–1604","1555–1640":"1555–1640","1560–1587":"1560–1587","1560–1604":"1560–1604","1541–1600":"1541–1600","1570–1604":"1570–1604","1570–1616":"1570–1616","1520–1600":"1520–1600","1535–1640":"1535–1640","1550":"1550","1560":"1560","1570":"1570","10 Jan 1540":"10. tammikuuta 1540","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1555":"1555","1587":"1587","1520":"1520","1541":"1541","1640":"1640","1585":"1585","1540":"1540","1616":"1616","1604":"1604","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Glasgow, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bothkennar, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Bothkennar, Stirlingshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"10 Jan 1540–1600":"10 janvier 1540–1600","1